{{italic title}} {{for|the 1951 film|Across the Wide Missouri (film)}} [[File:AcrossTheWideMissouriBook.jpg|thumb|First edition (publ. [[Houghton Mifflin]])]] '''''Across the Wide Missouri, With an Account of the Discovery of the Miller Collection'''''<ref>{{cite book|title=Across the Wide Missouri|isbn= 0-395-92497-9|date=1947|author=DeVoto, Bernard|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Across_the_Wide_Missouri.html?id=VoZBbdPhEKIC |website=books.google.com}}</ref> is a 1947 book by American historian [[Bernard DeVoto]]. It is the second volume of a trilogy that includes ''The Year of Decision'' (1942) and ''The Course of Empire'' (1952). ==Description== ''Across the Wide Missouri'' is a history of the [[fur trade]] in the [[American West]], during its peak in the 1830s. The trapping of [[American Beaver|beaver]] and other animals caused conflicts between the trappers and the various [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] tribes of the Upper [[Missouri River]] Basin. ==Reception== The book was awarded the [[Pulitzer Prize for History]] in 1948<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/prize-winners-by-year/1948 |title=1948 Pulitzer Prizes |publisher=The Pulitzer Prizes|accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref> and was adapted as [[Across the Wide Missouri (film)|an eponymous 1951 film]] starring [[Clark Gable]].
